# Report: Causes Behind the Rise in Oil Prices

## Introduction

The price of oil is a critical economic indicator that influences global markets, energy policies, and geopolitical relations. Over recent years, oil prices have experienced significant volatility, with notable surges driven by a complex interplay of supply, demand, geopolitical events, and market expectations. Understanding the reasons behind rising oil prices is essential for policymakers, investors, and consumers alike. This report provides a comprehensive analysis of the factors contributing to oil price increases, drawing upon recent data and expert analyses from reputable sources.

---

## Overview of Recent Oil Price Trends

Oil prices have seen a substantial rise since the lows experienced during the COVID-19 pandemic. For instance, Brent crude prices surged from approximately $18 per barrel in April 2020 to over $100 per barrel by February 2022, marking the first time since 2014 that prices reached this level ([McKinsey & Company, 2022](https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/oil-and-gas/our-insights/snapshot-of-global-oil-supply-and-demand-february-2022)).

This sharp increase reflects not only the recovery of global demand post-pandemic but also constrained supply and geopolitical tensions, notably the invasion of Ukraine in early 2022, which disrupted Russian oil exports and triggered sanctions.

---

## Key Drivers of Rising Oil Prices

### 1. **Supply Constraints**

#### a. OPEC+ Production Policies

OPEC and its allies (OPEC+) have played a pivotal role in managing oil supply. During the pandemic, they implemented significant production cuts to stabilize prices amid collapsing demand. As demand rebounded, OPEC+ has cautiously increased output but often below market expectations.

- In late 2021 and early 2022, OPEC+ production was approximately 700,000 barrels per day below targets, largely due to maintenance and investment issues in key African producers like Nigeria and Angola ([Reuters, 2021](https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/will-gasoline-prices-drop-2022-it-depends-opec-us-shale-2021-11-17/)).

- Saudi Arabia, the largest producer within OPEC, increased output modestly but maintained a conservative approach to avoid oversupply.

#### b. Non-OPEC Production Challenges

- Non-OPEC producers, including US shale oil, have been slow to ramp up production despite higher prices. This is due to capital discipline enforced by investors, labor and equipment shortages, and cautious market outlooks.

- US shale production increased by about 1.97 million barrels per day year-over-year in early 2022 but remained below pre-pandemic levels ([McKinsey & Company, 2022](https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/oil-and-gas/our-insights/snapshot-of-global-oil-supply-and-demand-february-2022)).

- Maintenance issues and geopolitical factors have also affected production in countries like Libya, Venezuela, and Iran.

#### c. Inventory Drawdowns

- Global commercial oil inventories have been drawn down significantly as demand outpaces supply, reducing the buffer that typically cushions price volatility.

- OECD inventories remained above pre-pandemic levels in 2020 but have since decreased sharply, contributing to tighter markets ([McKinsey & Company, 2021](https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/oil-and-gas/our-insights/global-oil-supply-and-demand-outlook-to-2040)).

### 2. **Demand Recovery and Growth**

#### a. Post-Pandemic Economic Rebound

- As global economies reopened, demand for oil surged, driven by transportation, industrial activity, and energy needs.

- Global liquids demand increased by 2.1 million barrels per day to 101.4 million barrels per day in early 2022, with Europe showing the largest month-over-month increase as demand returned to pre-pandemic levels ([McKinsey & Company, 2022](https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/oil-and-gas/our-insights/snapshot-of-global-oil-supply-and-demand-february-2022)).

#### b. Substitution Effects

- Rising natural gas and coal prices, particularly in Asia, led to increased oil consumption as a substitute for power generation, further tightening oil markets ([MARCA, 2021](https://www.marca.com/en/economy/us-news/2021/10/24/617a4b8e22601d2a6f8b45d7.html)).

#### c. Regional Demand Variations

- China’s LNG demand grew by 18% in 2021, reflecting robust industrial activity and energy needs.

- European demand fluctuated due to energy security concerns and substitution effects but generally increased amid low storage levels and geopolitical tensions.

### 3. **Geopolitical Factors**

- The invasion of Ukraine by Russia in 2022 led to sanctions and import bans on Russian crude oil by several countries, disrupting supply chains and forcing buyers to seek alternative sources at higher prices ([McKinsey & Company, 2022](https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/oil-and-gas/our-insights/snapshot-of-global-oil-supply-and-demand-february-2022)).

- Political instability and attacks on oil infrastructure in regions like Nigeria have added supply risks, contributing to price volatility ([MERLIN FLOWER, 2010](https://www.merlinflower.com/energy/what-is-behind-the-rise-in-oil-prices)).

### 4. **Market Expectations and Speculation**

- Oil prices reflect not only current supply and demand but also future expectations. Traders’ anticipation of tighter markets or geopolitical risks can drive prices higher even before physical shortages occur ([Federal Reserve Bank of New York, 2021](https://libertystreeteconomics.newyorkfed.org/2021/10/oil-prices-global-demand-expectations-and-near-term-global-inflation)).

- Financial speculation and derivatives trading have been debated as factors influencing volatility, though their impact is often secondary to fundamental supply-demand dynamics ([Council on Foreign Relations, 2016](https://www.cfr.org/report/oil-price-volatility-causes-effects-and-policy-implications)).

